Data Preprocessing - S&P 500

  • The following example makes use of S&P 500 data from Yahoo! Finance.
  • As we know the stock prices are not necessarily stationary.
  • Hence for our analysis we calculate the returns of S&P 500 which have a lower range when compared to the prices
In [3]:
# Setting up Data
import datetime as dt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import arch.data.sp500

st = dt.datetime(1988, 1, 1)
en = dt.datetime(2018, 1, 1)
data = arch.data.sp500.load()
market = data["Adj Close"]
returns = 100 * market.pct_change().dropna()
ax = returns.plot()
xlim = ax.set_xlim(returns.index.min(), returns.index.max())
plt.ylabel("Returns")
plt.title("S&P Returns vs. Time")
Out[3]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'S&P Returns vs. Time')
  • As we can see the returns are centered at zero, which is ideal
  • The variance/volatility in our time series is not constant over time. We can identify high volatile periods are around the great recession(2008-2009)
  • The Heteroskedasticity makes this data ideal for GARCH modelling
  • Now we will calculate the actual varying variance over time for our returns data
In [4]:
returns = pd.DataFrame(returns).rename(columns = {'Adj Close':'Returns'})
returns['Variance'] = 0

for i in range(len(returns) - 1):
    #returns.iloc[i+1,1] = np.array([returns.iloc[0:i+2,0]]).std()
    returns.iloc[i+1,1] = np.array([returns.iloc[i,0], returns.iloc[i+1,0]]).std()

Auto-correlation and Partial auto-correlation plots

  • Now we utilize the ACF and PACF plots to understand the time series better
  • This will give us an idea on the p,q values to be used in teh GARCH model
In [5]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf

num_lags = 50
acf_values = plot_acf(returns['Returns']**2, lags=num_lags, zero = True)
  • Even though the Auto correlation is decreasing, it doesn't converge until very high lags
  • We see some significant peaks till 11, suggesting a value of q = 11 in our model later
In [6]:
pacf_values = plot_pacf(returns['Returns']**2, lags=num_lags, zero = True)
  • The PACF has a better profile and coverges to zero at relatively lower number of lags
  • We see some significant peaks till 11, suggesting a value of q = 11 in our model later

GARCH (with a Constant Mean)

  • The default set of options produces a model with a constant mean, GARCH(1,1) conditional variance and normal errors. We will use this as a comparision for improved model later

  • We split the data into train and test set, and the model is estimated using the first 22 years to estimate parameters and then forecasts are produced for the final 8

In [7]:
# Garch analysis (with a constant mean)

from arch import arch_model

am = arch_model(returns['Returns'], vol='Garch', p=1, o=0, q=1)
split_date = dt.datetime(2010,1,1)
res = am.fit(last_obs=split_date)
print(res.summary())

Forecasted Variance

Analytical forecasts are available for most models that evolve in terms of the squares of the model residuals, e.g., GARCH, HARCH, etc.

Plotted the forecasted variance for the test set over 5 horizons. h.1 - One step ahead forecast, h.2 - Two step ahead forecast,... h.5 - Five step ahead forecast.

In [8]:
from arch.__future__ import reindexing

forecasts = res.forecast(horizon=5, start=split_date)
forecasts.variance[split_date:].plot()
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x179d5c894c0>

Actual Variance

Plotted the actual variance computed above for the test set.

In [9]:
returns.loc[split_date:, 'Variance'].plot()
Out[9]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x179dcd2b580>

On comparing the plots, we can say that the forecasted variance for the test set looks reasonable and it does align with the actual variance. This shows that the chosen Garch model is indeed a good fit.

The values in the columns h.1 are one-step ahead forecast, while values in h.2, , h.5 are 2, , 5 - observation ahead forecasts. The output is aligned so that the date column is the final data used to generate the forecast, so that h.1 in row 2018-12-31 is the one-step ahead forecast made using data up to and including December 31, 2018.

Fixing Parameters

In some circumstances, fixed rather than estimated parameters might be of interest. A model result-like class can be generated using the fix() method. The class returned is identical to the usual model result class except that information about inference (standard errors, t-stats, etc) is not available.

In the example, we fix the parameters to a symmetric version of the previously estimated model. We estimate the parameters by choosing values from the 95% confidence intervals in the above computed model.

In [12]:
# Fixing parameters

fixed_res = am.fix([0.0345, 0.01, 0.06, 0.912])   # mu, omega, alpha and beta values
print(fixed_res.summary())

Conclusion

  • From analysis we identified that a basic GARCH(1,1) model is able to identify the changing patterns in volatilty
  • Our forecasts don't necessarily improve much by selecting higher values of p and q suggesting a basic GARCH(1,1) as the appropriate model for the S&P 500 data chosen here
